textMap.PRIMARY: Bonus Content: This episode of "The Man In the High Castle" is one of a number of titles that benefit from exclusive videos and behind-the-scenes photos, accessible in the X-Ray Bonus tab in Prime Video.

The Liberty Bell was cast in 1752. It is made of a copper and tin alloy and bears an inscription from the Book of Leviticus: 'Proclaim liberty throughout all the land unto all the inhabitants thereof."
Werner Heisenberg, leading Nazi scientist was the pioneer of Quantum Theory.

When Helen Smith mentions Joseph Goebbels and his deformity to her therapist during a session she is referring to the Nazi minister's congenital clubfoot, which caused him to walk with a limp and could not be fixed via surgery.
Transference is an unproven psychological phenomenon proposed by Austrian neurologist Sigmund Freud, the father of psychoanalysis.
"Baku" is Kido's alias in the Neutral Zone, and it is also the name of a mythological Japanese creature that devours bad dreams.
People farm, trade and provide services in the Neutral Zone in a free-form market, reliant on supply and demand. Kido is aware of this culture and knows he can exploit it to gain intelligence.

Jefferson Market Women's House of Detention used to reside at 10 Greenwich Avenue on downtown Manhattan's West Side. The jail building was constructed in 1931 in the art deco style. It remains the only art-deco prison in recorded history.
On the eastern border of the Neutral Zone, unlike in the West, there are strict and thorough security checks in and out of the Reich. Passes are required.
